What people are saying
“Excellent arena staff”
Nov 2024
First time attending event using my mobility scooter so was really apprehensive that I would have problems getting it stored especially as the tickets were purchased when I was able to walk longer distances. Cannot speak highly enough about all the staff from the entrance gates through to taking us to our seats. We were guided to the elevator where someone was waiting to take anyone with mobility issues to the correct floor. There was then another member of staff who guided us to our seats in the VIP section and then helped my husband take the scooter to a large store room. After the very enjoyable André Rieu concert it was simple to get to the store room and reach the elevator to the exit. With a packed arena, it was amazing how quickly the audience were able to leave without any visible signs of any crush. The arena staff should really be congratulated for their efficiency and friendliness - I would now not hesitate to attend another show. Only slight criticism was that the arena seemed very hot and airless after the performance got underway - Would certainly wear lighter clothing in future.
“Depeche mode night”
Mar 2024
We are in Lisbon to attend the Depeche Mode concert which is our second concert of the European tour, with the first in May last year at the Ziggo dome in Amsterdam. The band were brilliant on both occasions but the Lisbon arena is a very poor venue. We had golden circle tickets same as Amsterdam but a totally different experience, too many fans packed in the space and the bar area totally disorganised only the one bar with two serving areas , they only sold 1/2 pint beers and small glasses of wine , in the uk arenas and in Amsterdam the bar areas are multiple and well organised? To be honest the acoustics in Lisbon were good but the overall fan experience very poor, we will definitely revisit the Ziggo dome in Amsterdam but never this arena in Lisbon

The area

Address
Neighborhood: Parque das Nações
This neighborhood was built up at the end of the 1990s mostly because of the Expo '98. The pavilions and structures that once were the home of all the Expo's attractions and exhibits are still culturally and artistically significant. In Parque das Nações you'll explore conference and concert pavilions, a shopping center, trendy restaurants and an enjoyable cable car ride you can't miss out on. On top of this, the amazing Lisbon Oceanarium (one of the most spectacular things you'll ever see in the city) will take your breath away: its respect and will to preserve natural wildlife is uncanny. Easily accessible by metro, bus or taxi from the city center, Parque das Nações is highly recommended for anyone who'll spend more than 3 days in the Portuguese capital.
How to get there
  • Oriente • 6 min walk
